Calls from a pair of adults near a nest with three well grown young, on a sea cliff.  The first series of harsher calls appear to be given in alarm at my presence, but then they start flying a large circle away from the nest, calling back and forth with the more nasal and bell-like calls.  During that part of the recording, one bird would give the bell-like calls (presumably the female), and the other would respond with the more nasal version (presumably the male).
NOTES: Adult recorded at nest on the side of a cabin. Young silent. Same nest recorded ML 132204. Habitat: Tundra, Arctic Tundra.

NOTES: Recorded simultaneously by Gerrit Vyn.  We found a pair of Corvus corax at a nest with two large nestlings.  The nest was placed in the antlers of a moose, which was hung on the side of a building in the ghost town, Happy Valley.  One of the adults alternated flying and perching on the house that the nest was on, vocalizing all the while. Photos of the nest are on file on a CD in the LNS edited cuts file under MJA.  We came back later to this nest and recorded the adults in MS stereo.  Never did we hear the nestlings vocalize.  Same pair/individual(s) as LNS 132204 (MS stereo recording). Sound stimulation was (other): Human presence near nest. Other Behaviors: Mob. Habitat: Tundra, Arctic Tundra.
